06279nam a22009015i 9780812299649DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122996497 a10.9783/97808122996492doi  a(DE-B1597)577462  a(OCoLC)1261364530  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBF175 7aHIS0150702bisacsh04a150.22231 aBar-Haim, Shaul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Maternalists :bPsychoanalysis, Motherhood, and the British Welfare State /cShaul Bar-Haim. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aIntellectual History of the Modern Age00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. The “Sphincter- Morality” and Beyond: The Concept of Childhood in Interwar Psychoanalysis -- tChapter 2. How Children Think: Susan Isaacs and “Primitive” Thinking -- tChapter 3. Malinowski, Róheim, and the Maternal Shift in British Psychoanalysis and Anthropology -- tChapter 4. Imagining the “Maternal” Past: Ian Suttie and the Critique of Oedipal Culture -- tChapter 5. What About Father? Civic- Republican Maternalism and the Welfare State -- tChapter 6. “The Drug ‘Doctor’ ”: The Balint Movement and Psychosocial Medicine in Postwar Britain -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Maternalists is a study of the hitherto unexplored significance of utopian visions of the state as a maternal entity in mid-twentieth century Britain. Demonstrating the affinities between welfarism, maternalism, and psychoanalysis, Shaul Bar-Haim suggests a new reading of the British welfare state as a political project.After the First World War, British doctors, social thinkers, educators, and policy makers became increasingly interested in the contemporary turn being made in psychoanalytic theory toward the role of motherhood in child development. These public figures used new notions of the "maternal" to criticize modern European culture, and especially its patriarchal domestic structure. This strand of thought was pioneered by figures who were well placed to disseminate their ideas into the higher echelons of British culture, education, and medical care. Figures such as the anthropologists Bronislaw Malinowski and Geza Róheim, and the psychiatrist Ian Suttie—to mention only a few of the "maternalists" discussed in the book—used psychoanalytic vocabulary to promote both imagined perceptions of motherhood and their idea of the "real" essence of the "maternal." In the 1930s, as European fascism took hold, the "maternal" became a cultural discourse of both collective social anxieties and fantasies, as well as a central concept in many strands of radical, and even utopian, political thinking. During the Second World War, and even more so in the postwar era, psychoanalysts such as D. W. Winnicott and Michael Balint responded to the horrors of the war by drawing on interwar maternalistic thought, making a demand to "maternalize" British society, and providing postwar Britain with a new political idiom for defining the welfare state as a project of collective care.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aMotherhoodxPolitical aspectszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotherhoodxPsychological aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aPsychoanalysisxHistoryy20th century. 0aPsychoanalysisxSocial aspectszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aWelfare statezGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aBritish psychoanalytic society.  aHistory of welfare policy.  aMaternalistic t